There are bad tidings for car makers as sales declined , following the country s downgrade to junk status for the period ended April. South Africa s new vehicle sales fell 13.4% year-on-year to 34 956 units compared to last year s 40348.Total vehicle sales figures measure cars, buses and heavy vehicles. Total sales averaged 39 812 from 1994 until 2017, reaching an all time high of 65 689 in August 2006 and a record low of 18 482 in September 1994. The low count affected all sectors of the industry, including light commercial vehicles that saw a decline of 13.3% from 12.217 to 10592, car sales from 26012 to 22452 representing a 13.7% decrease and truck categories were down by between 3.4% and 15.5%.Exports were down 25.5% compared to the prior period, dropping from 32 832 to 24 449. The National Association of Automobile Manufacturers of South Africa (Naamsa) said that the outlook for newvehicle sales became negative during the extraordinary political events at the end of March when President Jacob Zuma sacked former finance minister Pravin Gordhan. The organisation said that the lower sales could also be attributed to the many public holidays.-THELMA NGOMA|thelman@thenewage.co.za